			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: no twisting in eq2?<a name="37930"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 3 04 5:13 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>EQ2 is going to be a completely different game.  I'm a little disappointed, actually, by the level of negativity toward it people are voicing here.  Everyone is entitiled to their opinions, of course, but I think that for many folks, the only thing they really know about EQ2 is that they can't solo kite etc. and have simply dismissed it.  Imo, the game is worthy of a closer look than that.
<br />

<br />
To decide what class you would like in EQ2, you really need to look at the Archetypes:  Fighter, Mage, Priest, Scout, and Artisan.  Unless you like the utility and so on of the Scout Archetype, you probably won't like being a Bard either.
<br />

<br />
As far as overall game-play, however, I believe that with the possible exception of Bards, ALL the classes in eq2 will require greater activity and concentration to play well.  A good Fighter will not simply target a mob and hit &quot;A&quot; and click the right discipline for the fight.  Since groups will fight GROUPS of mobs (no single pulling, no mezzing), ALL the players, NOT just the CC classes, will have to do things like change targets a lot etc.
<br />

<br />
The &quot;Combat Wheel&quot; or &quot;Heroic Opportunity&quot; thingie in eq2 will create cool special attacks etc. based on the entire group working together and timing things correctly.  Scouts will have the distinction (in addition to tons of utitily like speed, stealth, tracking, lockpicking, traps handling etc.) of being able to manipulate the &quot;Combat Wheel&quot; where a group without a Scout basically gets one at random.  The Scout may decide that the group is low on healing power, for example, and may manipulate the fight in such a way that a super duper group heal comes up on the Wheel.  If they are short on DPS, they might choose to bring up the uber nuke one etc.
<br />

<br />
The opportunity for Scouts/Bards to be the &quot;leaders&quot; of groups, i.e. controlling the battle in similar fashion as Pulling and CC for a group in eq1, is definitely there, and makes it an attractive class to me.
<br />

<br />
Add to that the fact that many of the things that sucked about eq1:  timesinks, twinking, PL, KS, unreasonable amounts of competition for raid encounters...  All these things have been addressed in eq2.
<br />

<br />
Bards (and other casters) will be able to have multiple effects going at once.  This will simply be made easier on the wrists because the actuall activity of &quot;twisting&quot;, 1...2...3... etc. will be unneccesary.  That does NOT eliminate the REALLY cool part of being a Bard, which is flexibility and song selection.  You will still need to THINK, and choose the RIGHT songs, based on the composition of your group, and the mobs you are fighting etc.  What makes a good bard in eq1 will make a good bard in eq2 as well.  (Or any other class, for that matter, imo)
<br />

<br />
I will say this though:  If you prefer solo play, and want to be an uber solo class, you will not like eq2.  Solo play will be available, but imo, it's gonna be pretty lame.  The good thing is, that with the archetype system, it is MUCH less likely that people will sit for hours LFG because they aren't part of the &quot;holy trinity&quot; like in eq1 (Tank, Healer, CC/Slower/Haster).
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
